:::summary
Chinese philosophy is one of the oldest and most distinctive intellectual traditions in the world, flourishing for more than two and a half millennia across a civilization of extraordinary continuity and sophistication. The great schools of ancient China — Confucianism, Taoism, Legalism, and Mohism — arose during the turbulent "Hundred Schools of Thought" period (6th–3rd centuries BC), producing foundational texts that shaped East Asian civilization as profoundly as Plato and Aristotle shaped the West. Later, Buddhism flowed in from India and was reshaped by Chinese genius into distinctive schools — Chan (Zen), Pure Land, and Hua-yen — that are among the richest developments in world philosophy and religion.
:::

